# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In computer information systems, a **dashboard** is a type of graphical user interface which often provides at-a-glance views of data relevant to a particular objective or process through a combination of visualizations and summary information.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In other usage, "dashboard" is another name for "progress report" or "report" and is considered a form of data visualization.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The dashboard is often accessible by a web browser and is typically linked to regularly updating data sources.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are often interactive and facilitate users to explore the data themselves, usually by clicking into elements to view more detailed information.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The term dashboard originates from the automobile dashboard where drivers monitor the major functions at a glance via the instrument panel.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The idea of digital dashboards followed the study of decision support systems in the 1970s.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Early predecessors of the modern business dashboard were first developed in the 1980s in the form of Executive Information Systems (EISs).
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Due to problems primarily with data refreshing and handling, it was soon realized that the approach wasn't practical as information was often incomplete, unreliable, and spread across too many disparate sources.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Thus, EISs hibernated until the 1990s when the information age quickened pace and data warehousing, and online analytical processing (OLAP) allowed dashboards to function adequately.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Despite the availability of enabling technologies, the dashboard use didn't become popular until later in that decade, with the rise of key performance indicators (KPIs), and the introduction of Robert S.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In the late 1990s, Microsoft promoted a concept known as the Digital Nervous System and "digital dashboards" were described as being one leg of that concept.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Today, the use of dashboards forms an important part of Business Performance Management (BPM).
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Initially dashboards were used for monitoring purposes, now with the advancement of technology, dashboards are being used for more analytical purposes.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The use of dashboards has now been incorporating; scenario analysis, drill down capabilities, and presentation format flexibility.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards allow managers to monitor the contribution of the various departments in their organization.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In addition, they enable “rolling up” of information to present a consolidated view across an organization.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] To gauge exactly how well an organization is performing overall, digital dashboards allow you to capture and report specific data points from each department within the organization, thus providing a "snapshot" of performance.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards offers a holistic view of the entire business as it gives the manager a bird's eye view into the performance of sales, data inventory, web traffic, social media analytics and other associated data that is visually presented on a single dashboard.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards lead to better management of marketing/financial strategies as a dashboard for the display of marketing data makes the process of marketing easier and more reliable as compared to doing it manually.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Web analytics play a crucial role in shaping the marketing strategy of many businesses.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards also facilitate for better tracking of sales and financial reporting as the data is more precise and in one area.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Lastly, dashboards offer for better customer service through monitoring because they keep both the managers and the clients updated on the project progress through automated emails and notifications.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards can be broken down according to role and are either strategic, analytical, operational, or informational.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are the 3rd step on the information ladder, demonstrating the conversion of data to increasingly valuable insights.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards support managers at any level in an organization and provide the quick overview that decision-makers need to monitor the health and opportunities of the business.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards of this type focus on high-level measures of performance and forecasts.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards benefit from static snapshots of data (daily, weekly, monthly, and quarterly) that are not constantly changing from one moment to the next.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for analytical purposes often include more context, comparisons, and history, along with subtler performance evaluators.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In addition, analytical dashboards typically support interactions with the data, such as drilling down into the underlying details.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for monitoring operations are often designed differently from those that support strategic decision making or data analysis and often require monitoring of activities and events that are constantly changing and might require attention and response at a moment's notice.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards may be laid out to track the flows inherent in the business processes that they monitor.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Graphically, users may see the high-level processes and then drill down into low-level data.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] This level of detail is often buried deep within the corporate enterprise and otherwise unavailable to the senior executives.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Three main types of digital dashboards dominate the market today: desktop software applications, web-browser-based applications, and desktop applications are also known as desktop widgets.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Both Desktop and Browser-based providers enable the distribution of dashboards via a web browser.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] An example of the latter is web-based-browser Asana, which helps teams orchestrate their work, from daily tasks to strategic cross-functional initiatives.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] With it, teams can manage everything from company objectives to digital transformation to product launches and marketing campaigns.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Specialized dashboards may track all corporate functions.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Examples include human resources, recruiting, sales, operations, security, information technology, project management, customer relationship management, digital marketing and many more departmental dashboards.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For a smaller organization like a startup a compact startup scorecard dashboard tracks important activities across lot of domains ranging from social media to sales.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard projects involve business units as the driver and the information technology department as the enabler.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Therefore, the success of dashboard projects depends on the relevancy/importance of information provided within the dashboard.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] This includes the metrics chosen to monitor and the timeliness of the data forming those metrics; data must be up to date and accurate.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Key performance indicators, balanced scorecards, and sales performance figures are some of the content appropriate on business dashboards.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards involve the combination of visual and functional features.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] This combination of features helps improve cognition and interpretation.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] A performance dashboard sits at the intersection of two powerful disciplines: business intelligence and performance management.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Therefore, there are different users who could use these dashboards for different reasons.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, a level of workers could look at monitoring inventory while those in more managerial roles can look at lagging measure.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Then executives could utilize the dashboard to evaluate strategic performance against objectives.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Balanced scorecards and dashboards have been linked together as if they were interchangeable.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] However, although both visually display critical information, the difference is in the format: Scorecards can open the quality of an operation while dashboards provide calculated direction.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] A balanced scorecard has what they called a "prescriptive" format.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Each of these sections ensures that a Balanced Scorecard is essentially connected to the businesses critical strategic needs.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The design of a dashboard is more loosely defined.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are usually a series of graphics, charts, gauges and other visual indicators that can be monitored and interpreted.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Even when there is a strategic link, on a dashboard, it may not be noticed as such since objectives are not normally present on dashboards.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] However, dashboards can be customized to link their graphs and charts to strategic objectives.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard technology is available "out-of-the-box" from many software providers.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Some companies, however, continue to do in-house development and maintenance of dashboard applications.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, GE Aviation has developed a proprietary software/portal called "Digital Cockpit" to monitor the trends in the aircraft spare parts business.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] A good information design will clearly communicate key information to users and makes supporting information easily accessible.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] There are a few key elements to a good dashboard:.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] A research-based framework for Business Intelligence dashboard design suggests that "cross-visual interactivity" is the most impactful of all features.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards serve as a visual representation for a company to monitor progress and trends, not only among themselves but against other companies as well.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards and visualizations contain data that is updated in real time.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, if the underlying data in an Excel spreadsheet were to change, so would the visualization.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Power BI provides the tools for a user to create different types of visualizations to communicate the data that they are using.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Some examples of these visualizations include graphs, maps, and clustered columns.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Power BI pulls data from Excel that can be used to create dashboards and visualizations.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Whereas Excel does not import data from Power BI.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Excel is typically used for less data and Power BI is more complex.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Power BI can be used to display trends over time.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, a company can create a time plot that shows its costs and revenues over a certain period.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The data can then be arranged to show per day, month, quarter, year, etc.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] This requires simple formatting tools so the data can quickly be changed and compared.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Power BI allows the user to customize their visualizations by adding colors and labels.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In addition, when the user clicks a data point, they are able to understand what the point or selection is showing.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Power BI also has a commonly used map feature where businesses can view their sales and earnings across different states and countries.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Places with the highest amounts of data will appear larger in size.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, a state with the most revenue will be bigger than states with less data.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Power BI is also interactive in that in any type of map a person can expand a specific category to look deeper into the data contained.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Tableau is another program that allows users to create dashboards.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Allegedly, One of Tableau's biggest advantages is how much data it can hold.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Tableau can hold an unlimited amount, whereas an Excel spreadsheet has a capacity of 1,048,576 rows.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] However, it is possible to hold and analyze effectively billions of rows in Excel, using its Power Pivot feature.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Tableau has the ability to make interactive dashboards by clicking into a specific point.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, you can have data be displayed within a map.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] By clicking a specific state or city you can get a closer look at the data contained within that location.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Filters and parameters can also be added.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] For example, if one were to analyze revenues across the United States you could set a parameter to only show salaries within a particular range.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Once set, only states within this range will be highlighted.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Excel has many tools that help the user not only implement data but also visualize data.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Excel has many built in functions that can help break down data and also separate data by scenarios.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The user can easily download and add files to their Excel sheets to use for their data.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Other tools Excel offers is the use of conditional formatting and basic pivot tables and charts.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Excel allows the user to reference other cells which ultimately allows for complex computations to be made and conclusions to be drawn from data.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] There are certain guidelines that can be useful when creating dashboards and other visualizations.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The guidelines have a structure that can be followed and that is beginning with reading direction.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] When it comes to how you are arranging your information on your dashboard or a visualization it can be helpful to think about reading direction.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] General reading direction is from left to right and from top to bottom.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Having information flow in this structure will allow others to read and understand your visuals in a more natural structure.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Local proximity is another idea to keep in mind when creating a visual or a dashboard.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Having information in a close proximity can be compared with a better effectiveness and allow users to draw conclusions.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Being able to make sure the user is not being overloaded with information when creating your visual.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Having a few key figures with significant importance can be more helpful compared to having too much information.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] When you have too much information and not a structure to what you are presenting then that is known as a “data graveyard”.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Another aspect to keep in mind while creating visuals that goes along with information overload is the idea of interaction within your visual.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Interacting with the dashboard would allow for further detail to be obtained from the user and allow them to better understand the information on your dashboard.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Chart visualization is an important aspect when creating dashboards, diagrams in particular.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] When you have complex data it can be difficult to come to conclusions from that material and being able to have different visual elements within the dashboard can be helpful in giving a larger overview of the material.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Being able to have a visual reporting system allows multiple processing operations to be carried out and that could increase the effectiveness of decisions.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] There are different types of visualizations that can be seen as more effective depending on the data type and the recipient.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Looking at traditional business graphics in an interactive form is another aspect to keep in mind when creating a dashboard.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Business charts are used mainly in the form of interactive dashboards.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] A major advantage of business charts is that the majority of users have an understanding of them.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] There are many connections between dashboards and accounting.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards aid with budgeting, management control, and wage control.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used to present data in a quick and easy to read way.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The ability to present data in a quick way with a visual allows for more data to be processed and understood.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used for performance reports, sales analysis on sectors, and inventory rotation.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards should be quick visualizations that allow decisions to be made quicker than they usually would without the access to dashboard technology.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are also used in accounting decision making settings.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] The data can help prove a change is efficient or inefficient and therefore help with improving systems throughout an organization.
[src:elastic-security/dashboard-computing] In order for a dashboard to be efficient, the individual creating the dashboard needs to make sure that the information is simple and easy to read and be interpreted.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] In 2004 Shay Banon developed a recipe software application for his wife, who was studying at Le Cordon Bleu.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] He built Elasticsearch in 2009 and spent three years developing the product along with the open-source community.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] In 2012, he co-founded the company Elasticsearch with Simon Willnauer, Steven Schuurman, and Uri Boness.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] After the company acquired Found in 2015, the company rebranded as Elastic.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] While the company had been informally referred to as Elastic since its inception, it was not its official name.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] In November 2022, Elastic NV laid off 13% of its workforce.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] In June 2026, 7% of the global workforce was laid off.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] Software developed by the company includes Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] As a stack, these have been referred to by the company as the Elastic Stack or ELK Stack.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] The company also offers Elastic Cloud as an SaaS, and Elastic Cloud Enterprise (ECE).
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] Elasticsearch technology is used by eBay, Wikipedia, Yelp, Uber, Lyft, Tinder, and Netflix.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] The company also offers Search AI Lake and related services to provide ElasticSearch services for large data lakes.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] Elastic is a distributed company, which means its workforce is distributed globally.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] Accordingly, Elastic does not have a principal executive office.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] Elastic is registered with the trade register of the Dutch Chamber of Commerce under number 54655870 and the principal registered office is at Keizersgracht 281, 1016 ED Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
[src:elastic-security/elastic-nv] The company is headquartered in Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is distributed and uses JSON documents stored in indices divided into shards, each of which may have replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] It supports full-text search, faceted search, real-time search, and multitenancy.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] The software is developed alongside Logstash, Kibana, and Beats as part of the Elastic Stack (formerly the ELK Stack).
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Shay Banon created the precursor to Elasticsearch, called Compass, in 2004.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Developing a third version of Compass, he concluded that a full rewrite was necessary to build a scalable, distributed search solution using JSON over HTTP as a common interface.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] He released the first version of Elasticsearch in February 2010.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elastic NV was founded in 2012 to provide commercial services and products around Elasticsearch and related software.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In June 2014, the company raised $70 million in a Series C funding round led by New Enterprise Associates, with additional funding from Benchmark Capital and Index Ventures, bringing total funding to $104 million.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In March 2015, the company changed its name from *Elasticsearch* to *Elastic* and, through the acquisition of Found, launched a managed cloud offering later known as Elastic Cloud.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In November 2017, Elastic acquired the search startup Swiftype, whose technology became the basis for Elastic App Search and Elastic Site Search.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elastic also formed partnerships with Google to offer Elastic Cloud on Google Cloud Platform and with Alibaba to offer Elasticsearch and Kibana on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In June 2018, Elastic filed for an initial public offering with an estimated valuation of between $1.5 and $3 billion.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] On 5 October 2018, Elastic was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In January 2021, Elastic announced that starting with version 7.11, Elasticsearch and Kibana would be relicensed from Apache License 2.0 to a dual license under the Server Side Public License and the Elastic License, neither of which is recognised as an open-source license.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elastic stated the change was a response to Amazon Web Services (AWS) offering Elasticsearch and Kibana as a service without what Elastic described as adequate collaboration.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Critics of the change noted that Elastic had previously promised never to alter the Apache 2.0 licensing of Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash, and predicted the move would damage the ecosystem.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] AWS responded by announcing a fork of the projects to continue development under Apache License 2.0.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Other members of the Elasticsearch ecosystem, including Logz.io, CrateDB, and Aiven, also committed to supporting a fork.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Due to potential trademark conflicts with the name "Elasticsearch", AWS rebranded their fork as OpenSearch in April 2021.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option for Elasticsearch starting with version 8.16.0.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] This made the software available under a free and open-source license once again alongside the two source-available options.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is built on Apache Lucene and exposes Lucene's capabilities through a JSON and Java API.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Documents are stored in indices, which are divided into primary shards; each shard may have zero or more replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Routing and rebalancing are handled automatically.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Once an index has been created, the number of primary shards cannot be changed.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] The engine supports faceted search and percolation, a form of prospective search in which stored queries are matched against incoming documents rather than the reverse.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] A gateway module handles long-term index persistence, allowing an index to be recovered after a node failure.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Real-time GET requests make Elasticsearch usable as a NoSQL datastore, though it does not support distributed transactions.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] In May 2019, Elastic made the core security features of the Elastic Stack available without charge, including TLS for encrypted communications, file and native realm authentication, and role-based access control for cluster APIs and indices.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] The corresponding source code is available under the Elastic License.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch also offers SIEM and machine learning capabilities as part of its commercial offerings.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Official client libraries are maintained for Java, C# (.NET), PHP, Python, and Ruby, among others.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is developed alongside Logstash (a data collection and log-parsing engine), Kibana (an analytics and visualisation platform), and Beats (lightweight data shippers).
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] The four products are designed for use together as the Elastic Stack.
[src:elastic-security/elasticsearch] The combination was previously known as the ELK Stack, an initialism for "Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana".
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] In text retrieval, **full-text search** refers to a set of techniques for searching a single computer-stored document or a collection in a full-text database.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Full-text search is distinguished from searches based on metadata or on specific parts of documents, such as titles, abstracts, selected sections, or bibliographical references.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] In a full-text search, a search engine examines the words in stored documents to find matches for user queries.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Full-text-search techniques began to appear in the 1960s (for example, IBM STAIRS in 1969), and became common in online bibliographic databases during the 1990s.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Many websites and application programs, including word processors, implement full-text search functionality.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Some web search engines, such as the former AltaVista, indexed the full text of web pages, while others indexed only selected portions of pages.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] When dealing with a small number of documents, a full-text-search engine can scan the contents of each document directly for every query, a strategy known as "serial scanning." Some tools, such as grep, operate in this way.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] When the number of documents or queries is large, full-text search is typically divided into two tasks: indexing and searching.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] During indexing, the engine scans all documents and builds a list of search terms, often called an index, or more precisely, a concordance.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] During the search stage, queries are performed against the index rather than the original documents.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The indexer records each term found in a document and may note its position within the text.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Common words, known as stop words (for instance, "the" or "and"), are omitted because they add little value to search results.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The diagram at the right illustrates a search with low recall and low precision.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] In the diagram, red and green dots represent the total population of potential search results for a given query, with green dots indicating relevant results and red indicating irrelevant results.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Relevance is indicated by proximity to the center of the inner circle.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The results actually returned by the search are highlighted on a light-blue background.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] In the example, only one relevant result of three possible relevant results was returned, giving a recall of ⅓ (33%).
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The precision is 1/4 (25%), since only one of the four results returned was relevant.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Due to the ambiguities of natural language, full-text-search systems typically include features such as filtering to increase precision and stemming to increase recall.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Controlled-vocabulary search can also help alleviate low-precision results by tagging documents to reduce ambiguity.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] There is generally a trade-off between precision and recall: increasing precision can reduce overall recall, while increasing recall may lower precision.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Full-text search can retrieve many documents that are not relevant to the intended query.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Such documents are called **false positives** (see Type I error).
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The retrieval of irrelevant documents is often caused by the inherent ambiguity of natural language.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] In the accompanying diagram, false positives are represented by irrelevant results (red dots) that were returned by the search (highlighted on a light-blue background).
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] At a basic level, search engines return items that contain the exact phrase listed in the query.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Tools and methodologies exist to account for grammatical or typographical errors and to refine results; however, these techniques still typically require a close textual match.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Because there are often multiple ways to refer to an entity or concept, full-text search may fail to retrieve an item if the exact term is not used in the query.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Not to be confused with semantic search, synonyms can be retrieved by creating an index of related terms, such that when a variation of a word is searched, items containing any of the related terms may also be returned.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The limitations of full-text searching have been addressed in two ways: by providing users with tools to express search questions more precisely, and by developing algorithms that improve retrieval precision.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] The following is a partial list of software products that support full-text indexing and search.
[src:elastic-security/full-text-search] Some of these are accompanied by documentation describing their architecture or algorithms, which may provide additional insight into how full-text search is implemented.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Kibana is a component of the Elastic Stack, a collection of tools for ingesting, storing, and querying log and event data.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The stack was originally called the ELK stack after its three original components: Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Elastic NV renamed it the Elastic Stack in 2015 when it added Beats, a family of lightweight data shippers.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Kibana was originally released under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In January 2021, Elastic re-licensed it under the proprietary Elastic License 2.0 and the Server Side Public License, removing it from open-source distribution.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option, making the source again available under an OSI-approved free and open-source license.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Kibana was created by Rashid Khan in 2013 as a front end for Elasticsearch.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The project was released under the Apache License 2.0 and quickly adopted alongside Elasticsearch and Logstash.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The three tools together became known as the ELK stack, a common pattern for centralizing and searching log data.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In 2015, Elastic NV, the company behind all three tools, rebranded the ELK stack as the Elastic Stack after introducing Beats, a set of lightweight agents for shipping data to Elasticsearch.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Kibana became the standard visualization layer of that stack.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Elastic provides Beats packages that include pre-built Kibana dashboards for common database and application technologies.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In October 2018, Elastic shipped **Canvas**, a presentation feature within Kibana that lets users build slide decks pulling live data directly from Elasticsearch.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In December 2019, Elastic introduced **Lens**, a drag and drop interface for building visualizations without writing aggregation queries.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In January 2021, Elastic re-licensed both Elasticsearch and Kibana from the Apache License 2.0 to the Elastic License 2.0 and the Server Side Public License (SSPL).
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Elastic cited cloud providers offering Elasticsearch as a managed service without contributing back to the project as the reason for the change.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Neither the Elastic License 2.0 nor the SSPL is approved by the Open Source Initiative, so the re-licensed versions were no longer considered open source by that definition.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In response, Amazon Web Services forked both Elasticsearch and Kibana at their last Apache-licensed versions.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The resulting projects, released in April 2021 under the name OpenSearch, included **OpenSearch Dashboards** as the Kibana-derived visualization component.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License (AGPLv3) as a third licensing option for both Elasticsearch and Kibana, allowing use under an OSI-approved license.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The Elastic License 2.0 and SSPL options remain available alongside AGPLv3.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Kibana runs as a Node.js web server that connects to an Elasticsearch cluster over its REST API.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The browser-based frontend is written in TypeScript and React.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] All persistent state, including saved searches, visualization definitions, and dashboard configurations, is stored as JSON documents in a dedicated Elasticsearch index.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Kibana exposes a query interface based on the Kibana Query Language (KQL), a simplified syntax for filtering documents by field values.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] It also supports the older Lucene query syntax and Elasticsearch SQL for users who require full query expressiveness.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The plugin architecture allows additional capabilities to be packaged and loaded at startup.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Elastic ships several first-party plugins, including Maps (geospatial visualization), Canvas, Lens, and the Observability and Security solution views.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Third-party plugins can be installed from the command line.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] Logstash provides a common input path to Elasticsearch for structured and unstructured log data, which Kibana then surfaces through dashboards.
[src:elastic-security/kibana] The Elastic Stack also supports ingestion directly through Beats agents or the Elasticsearch ingest pipeline without Logstash.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:elastic-security/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
